\section{Historical daily weather (BioSIM)}{

BioSIM provides modelled daily North American weather. The
\code{ClimaticEx_Daily} model exposes columns \code{Prcp}, \code{Tmin}, \code{Tmax}, \code{Tair},
\code{RelH}, \code{WndS}, \code{WndD}, \code{SRad}. Pass the corresponding lowercase variable
names to \code{vars} (e.g. \code{c("prcp", "tmax", "tmin", "rh", "ws", "wnddir", "srad")}).
}

\section{Historical monthly weather (TerraClim)}{

Terra Climate provides monthly North American weather 1980-present
(\url{https://www.climatologylab.org/terraclimate.html}).
TerraClim variables: \code{aet}, \code{def}, \code{PDSI}, \code{pet}, \code{ppt}, \code{q}, \code{soil}, \code{srad},
\code{swe}, \code{tmax}, \code{tmin}, \code{vap}, \code{vpd}, \code{ws}.
Use \code{\link[=prep_monthly_weather]{prep_monthly_weather()}} for TerraClim weather data.
}

\section{Historical monthly weather (BioSIM)}{

BioSIM's \code{Climatic_Monthly} model exposes columns \code{TotalPrcp}, \code{MeanTmin},
\code{MeanTmax}, \code{MeanTair}, \code{MeanRelH}, \code{TotalRadiation} (among others); wind
variables come from a companion \code{ClimaticWind_Monthly} model fetched in the
same call (\code{WindSpeed} plus 36 directional-frequency columns \code{W0}..\code{W350},
from which a frequency-weighted circular-mean wind from-direction is
computed). Pass the corresponding lowercase variable names to \code{vars} (e.g.
\code{c("prcp", "tmax", "tmin", "temp", "rh", "srad", "ws", "wnddir")}).
Use \code{\link[=prep_monthly_weather_biosim]{prep_monthly_weather_biosim()}} for BioSIM monthly weather.
}

\section{Historical monthly weather (climr)}{

\pkg{climr} provides ClimateNA-style change-factor downscaling against a
PRISM/DAYMET composite reference grid for North America, with observational
time series spanning 1901-2024
(\code{obs_ts_dataset = "climatena"} or \code{"cru.gpcc"}). Supported lowercase
\code{vars}: \code{prcp}, \code{tmax}, \code{tmin}, \code{temp}, \code{rh}, \code{srad}, \code{cmd} (climatic
moisture deficit). Wind variables (\code{ws}, \code{wnddir}) are \strong{not} provided by
climr - use \code{\link[=prep_monthly_weather_biosim]{prep_monthly_weather_biosim()}} for wind. Use
\code{\link[=prep_monthly_weather_climr]{prep_monthly_weather_climr()}} for climr monthly weather.
}

\section{Climate projections (BioSIM, CMIP5)}{

\code{\link[=prep_daily_weather]{prep_daily_weather()}} and \code{\link[=prep_monthly_weather_biosim]{prep_monthly_weather_biosim()}} accept \code{rcp} and
\code{clim_model} arguments that are forwarded to BioSIM. \code{rcp} is one of
\code{"CONSTANT_CLIMATE"} (1991-2020 climate replayed), \code{"RCP45"}, or \code{"RCP85"}.
\code{clim_model} is one of \code{"RCM4"} (Canadian Regional Climate Model 4,
CanESM2-driven), \code{"GCM4"} (CGCM4 / CanESM2-family GCM), or \code{"Hadley"}
(HadGEM). For years within BioSIM's observational range these arguments
have no effect on the returned data; they always namespace the on-disk
cache (\verb{<rcp>_<clim_model>} subdirectory under \verb{<studyArea_hash>/}).
}

\section{Climate projections (climr, CMIP6)}{

\code{\link[=prep_monthly_weather_climr]{prep_monthly_weather_climr()}} accepts \code{gcms}, \code{ssps}, and \code{max_run}
arguments forwarded to \code{\link[climr:downscale]{climr::downscale()}} for CMIP6 GCM projections. When
\code{gcms} is \code{NULL} the function runs in observational mode; otherwise it runs
in projection mode using \code{gcm_ssp_years = years}. The bcgov-recommended
eight-member ensemble subset is exposed as the package constant
\code{\link{climr_ensemble_8}}; pass \code{gcms = climr_ensemble_8} to use it.
\code{\link[=assemble_climate_library_file_monthly_climr]{assemble_climate_library_file_monthly_climr()}} averages over GCMs and SSPs
to give a single LANDIS-II-compatible value per \verb{(Year, Month, EcoID, Variable)}. See \code{\link[climr:list_gcms]{climr::list_gcms()}}, \code{\link[climr:list_ssps]{climr::list_ssps()}} for the full
choice sets.
}

\section{Rate-limiting}{

BioSIM is a remote web service. When parallelizing over batches/years (e.g.
with \code{future::plan(multisession)}), keep the worker count modest (\eqn{\le}
4) to avoid hammering the service.
}

\section{Caching}{

Per-batch / per-year BioSIM fetches are cached as Arrow CSV partitions under
the directory given by \code{getOption("landisutils.cache.path")}. Re-runs that
find an existing partition skip the BioSIM call.
\code{\link[=prep_monthly_weather_climr]{prep_monthly_weather_climr()}} relies on climr's own on-disk cache instead;
the cache root is \code{getOption("climr.cache.path")}, defaulting (for the
duration of the call) to \code{file.path(getOption("landisutils.cache.path"), "climr")} when unset.
}

\section{Topographic considerations}{

The climate data sources used by this package (BioSIM, Daymet, TerraClim)
are \strong{not PRISM-derived}.
PRISM (\url{https://prism.oregonstate.edu/}) applies topographically-aware
interpolation (slope, aspect, elevation, coastal proximity, temperature
inversions) when downscaling station observations to a grid
(Daly et al. 2008); the sources wrapped here use simpler interpolation
schemes that can produce \strong{large discrepancies in areas of complex
topography} (mountainous terrain, steep elevation gradients, rain
shadows): inter-product differences of 5-60\% in annual precipitation
(Henn et al. 2018) and >6 \eqn{^\circ}C in temperature (Walton & Hall
2018) have been documented in the western US.
Carefully evaluate the suitability of the chosen source for your study
area, especially in topographically heterogeneous landscapes.
}

